:: Epilogue {"position":"1150,100","size":"100,100"}
(if: $endingTag is "prof-complied")[
## Six weeks later.

You get your student evaluations. They are excellent. "Fair grader." "Consistent." "Explains the rubric clearly."

In March, you walk across campus and notice a flyer pinned to a bulletin board: “Carolina Students of Color: Testimonies about Grading.” There are photos beneath the headline, and one of them is Aisha. She is holding a sign that reads, “It flagged me before it read me.” You keep walking. Your tenure packet is still unfinished, and in it, you write that you have “embraced AI-augmented teaching.” The committee approves it unanimously.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "prof-mixed")[
## Six weeks later.

(if: $aishaOutcome is "accepted" or $aishaOutcome is "accepted-after-escalation")[Aisha emails you. Her scholarship committee flagged her term GPA. She wants to know if there's anything she can do. You write back that you can't change a submitted grade. You cc the chair. The chair doesn't reply.]
(else:)[Aisha emails to thank you for the A-. Her scholarship is safe for another semester. You file the email and don't reply.]

(if: $jordanOutcome is "passed")[Jordan graduates with honors.](else-if: $jordanOutcome is "downgraded")[Jordan does not graduate with honors. His father called the dean about it. The dean did not call you, and you take that as its own kind of message.](else:)[The honor referral on Jordan was dismissed for lack of corroboration. He graduates with honors anyway. His father sends the dean a thank-you note.] (if: $marcusOutcome is "accepted")[Marcus transfers to a community college. You don't see his name again.](else-if: $marcusOutcome is "split")[Marcus stays on, scholarship intact. You read his next paper and can tell he has started writing for the rubric.](else:)[Marcus emails you in November to say he's declared an English minor. He attaches a draft. It's good.]

At your next faculty meeting, the dean announces that the department renewed the GradeAssist contract for three more years. You vote in favor. It's a voice vote. Your voice is small.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "prof-resisted")[
## Six weeks later.

Your Vendor Relations meeting happens on a Tuesday at 2 PM. A consultant named Brian tells you, pleasantly, that your override rate is //"a data point, not a verdict."// He asks if you've considered that your assessments might be introducing //"human bias the tool is designed to correct."//

You ask to see the training data GradeAssist was calibrated on. Brian explains that's proprietary and covered under the vendor contract, a document you've never actually been shown.

Your tenure packet is due in six weeks. A note from the chair sits in your inbox: //"Elena, let's talk about the override issue before Friday."// You don't know yet what you'll tell him.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "prof-spoke-up")[
## Six weeks later.

Your email started something. Four other faculty have since filed formal concerns. Dr. Park has collected them into a report for the faculty senate. The Daily Tar Heel has published two articles. One quoted an anonymous international student who said: //"The tool decided I was cheating before anyone read what I wrote."//

The administration hasn't changed the contract. It has, however, issued a statement about its //"commitment to the responsible use of AI in assessment."//

Your department chair calls you in. He doesn't threaten you. He tells you, kindly, that your tenure case "will be a little more complicated this year." He says he's on your side. You believe him, partly.

Aisha is still at Carolina. (if: $aishaOutcome is "accepted" or $aishaOutcome is "accepted-after-escalation")[The C+ stayed in her transcript. She's still on her scholarship, barely.](else:)[The A− you overrode to stuck. She's still on her scholarship.] The contract has two more years left.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "stud-honest-punished")[
## Three months later.

You emailed your appeal at 10:15 AM, with the Google Doc version history attached. A reply came four days later: version history is "suggestive, but not dispositive." Your zero was upheld. A notation went on your academic record.

You don't retake COMP380. You switch majors to avoid it. You drop the ML class. Kenzie graduates on time and uses ChatGPT for her honors thesis. Nothing flags her. She gets into a master's program.

You're still here. You've got a 2.9. The COMP380 syllabus for next year now includes a sentence in red: //"OriginalCheck has been calibrated with updated training data and demonstrates improved cross-dialect fairness."// You don't know if that's true. There's no way to know.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "stud-hybrid-punished")[
## Three months later.

You appealed. Four days later, a reply: version history is "suggestive, but not dispositive." Your zero was upheld.

You didn't contest further. You decided the cost of an integrity case on your record was worse than the grade. You wrote parts of that essay with a machine and parts of it yourself, and the system didn't distinguish between them. You're not sure, looking back, whether you were innocent of what they accused you of. You're sure the tool couldn't have known.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "stud-silent")[
## Three months later.

You accepted the zero. Your semester GPA dropped below your scholarship minimum. You signed an agreement that the matter is closed. You didn't tell your parents.

Your parents find out in May. The conversation is bad. You transfer for the fall semester. You do well at the new school. Their writing program doesn't use OriginalCheck. You find you can write again when no one's grading the shape of your sentences.

The transfer costs you a year and seven thousand dollars.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "stud-spoke-up")[
## Three months later.

You signed the letter. In the free-text field you typed: //"I used AI for most of my essay. OriginalCheck cleared me. I'm signing this because a classmate who didn't use AI was flagged instead, and that's what the tool is actually measuring: not cheating, but the shape of someone's native English."//

The letter went public that Friday. Your anonymous quote was used in three articles. Dr. Park cited it in a faculty senate report.

The contract wasn't canceled. OriginalCheck issued a statement about "continuing to improve cross-dialect calibration." Aisha is still on her scholarship. Her grade wasn't changed, but she got what the chair called a "goodwill adjustment" on a later assignment.

You never told her it was you who signed the letter. You're not sure why.
]
(else-if: $endingTag is "stud-silent-user")[
## Three months later.

You graduated on time. You got the A−. You kept the scholarship. You never signed.

You still use ChatGPT for most of your writing. You've gotten better at disguising it. You sit down to write a birthday card to your sister and the cursor blinks for nine minutes before you open a new tab. You tell yourself it's not the same.

Aisha defended her honors thesis in May. You went. You didn't introduce yourself. After, in the hallway, a friend said //"that girl is so brave"// and you nodded. You think sometimes about the tightness you used to feel. You don't feel it anymore. You don't know if that's the system working right or working on you.
]

---

## A note before you close the tab.

You played one path. There are two. We wrote it that way on purpose: a professor at 1 AM doesn't see what the student is doing at their desk, and a flagged student doesn't see who clicked ACCEPT. The institution keeps them apart, so the project does too.

No ending here is the right one. We tried to make compliance feel as costly as resistance, because that's what our sources kept saying: there's no clean exit from inside the system.

(if: $endingTag is "prof-complied" or $endingTag is "stud-silent-user")[> Your ending is one where the system absorbs you. You didn't break the rules. You didn't change them either.]
(else-if: $endingTag is "prof-resisted" or $endingTag is "prof-spoke-up" or $endingTag is "stud-spoke-up")[> Your ending is one where you pushed back. You didn't win. Pushing back rarely wins on its own, but it sometimes makes winning possible later, for someone you won't meet.]
(else-if: $endingTag is "stud-honest-punished" or $endingTag is "stud-hybrid-punished")[> Your ending is one where the tool was wrong and the institution went with the tool anyway. This happens a lot.]
(else:)[> Your ending sits between compliance and resistance. Most of them do.]

If you want to see the other path, you can [[restart->Start]], but ask yourself first whether the urge to find the "right" ending is the same habit the system teaches.


:: Intro {"position":"275,100","size":"100,100"}
It is the fall semester at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

The College of Arts & Sciences has signed a three-year contract with ''GradeAssist'', an AI-powered rubric engine, and ''OriginalCheck'', an AI-text detector. Every undergraduate essay in the college now passes through both before a human sees it.

Students are prohibited from using generative AI for coursework. Faculty are //encouraged// to use it for grading.

The department posted a memo on the first day of class:

"These tools exist to support faculty workload and ensure fair, consistent evaluation. Questions about methodology should be directed to the Vendor Relations office."

Tonight, you're one of two people inside this system.

[[Choose who you are->RoleSelect]]


:: ProfEscalate {"position":"825,225","size":"100,100"}
You open your email to Dr. Halverson, the department chair. You write: //"I am seeing a pattern in GradeAssist/OriginalCheck outputs that appears to disadvantage non-native English writers and students who don't conform to the five-paragraph convention."//

You hit send at 8:47 PM. An auto-reply bounces back: //"Dr. Halverson is at a conference. For urgent GradeAssist concerns, contact Vendor Relations."//

You stare at the essay for a long time. Grades are due Monday and you still have to decide what Aisha gets.

(link: "Submit the AI grade. Deal with the chair later.")[
(set: $aishaOutcome to "accepted-after-escalation")
(set: $time to it - 1)
(go-to: "ProfEssay2")
]

(link: "Override anyway. Two forms of evidence are better than one.")[
(set: $aishaOutcome to "overridden-after-escalation")
(set: $overrides to it + 1)
(set: $credibility to it - 6)
(set: $time to it - 2)
(go-to: "ProfEssay2")
]


:: ProfEssay1 {"position":"575,100","size":"100,100"}
(set: $role to "professor")
(set: $time to 14)
(set: $credibility to 72)

It's 8:14 PM, Sunday. Forty essays to finalize by 9 AM Monday. You've already worked through the first eighteen. GradeAssist has pre-scored each paper; your job is to "review and confirm." You've accepted eighteen in a row so far.

You open essay nineteen. It's Aisha Al-Mansoori's.

<div class="screen">
''GradeAssist v4.2 · Essay Review''

Student: Al-Mansoori, Aisha (international, F-1 visa, 3rd-year)
Prompt: "Is algorithmic governance compatible with democratic consent?"
GradeAssist Score: (color: "#922")[C+ (76)]
OriginalCheck: (color: "#922")[89% likely AI-generated]
Flags: "Over-polished syntax," "atypical clause structure," "lexical density 2.3σ above cohort mean"
</div>

You read the essay yourself. It's, in your honest judgment, the most thoughtful paper in the stack. Aisha’s essay examines how technological systems gain authority when the people affected by them do not fully understand how they work. She connects historical examples of computerized governance to broader questions about consent, transparency, and legitimacy. Her central question is whether a system can still be considered fair or democratic when its decision-making process remains opaque.

You remember her in office hours, asking you to explain the difference between "argue" and "claim" as English is her second language. 

GradeAssist penalized her for not using a five-paragraph structure. OriginalCheck flagged her for writing //too cleanly//, which is a thing you didn't think you'd ever read in a sentence.

(link: "Accept the C+ and submit. You have 21 essays left.")[
(set: $aishaOutcome to "accepted")
(set: $credibility to it + 2)
(set: $time to it - 1)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfEssay2")
]

(link: "Override. Give the grade you believe the essay earned.")[
(set: $aishaOutcome to "overridden")
(set: $credibility to it - 8)
(set: $overrides to it + 1)
(set: $time to it - 2)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfEssay2")
]

(link: "Email the department chair. This is a pattern.")[
(set: $escalated to true)
(set: $credibility to it - 15)
(set: $time to it - 2)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfEscalate")
]


:: ProfEssay2 {"position":"575,225","size":"100,100"}
(if: $aishaOutcome is "accepted")[You click ACCEPT & SUBMIT and confirm the C+. Aisha will see this grade Tuesday morning. You know she will not contest it (international students rarely do) and the grade will factor into whether her scholarship renews.]
(else-if: $aishaOutcome is "overridden")[You override to A-. A dialog demands a 250-word justification, logged in your annual review packet. You type it and submit.]
(else-if: $aishaOutcome is "accepted-after-escalation")[You submit the C+. The chair's auto-reply is still sitting in your sent folder, unanswered.]
(else-if: $aishaOutcome is "overridden-after-escalation")[You override to A-. You attach your email to the chair as the justification.]

The next essay in the queue is Jordan Peters's.

<div class="screen">
''GradeAssist v4.2 - Essay Review''

Student: Peters, Jordan (legacy admit, 4th-year, pre-law)
GradeAssist Score: (color: "#262")[A- (91)]
OriginalCheck: (color: "#262")[3% likely AI-generated]
Flags: "Exemplary rubric compliance," "textbook five-paragraph structure"
</div>

You read it. The essay is competent. It hits every rubric box. It's also, unmistakably, AI-assisted. You know because Jordan came to office hours last week to ask what "epistemic humility" meant, and the phrase shows up twice in this paper. You know because AI has a very distinct way of writing. 

But both the institutional devices have cleared him.

(link: "Accept. Without a flag, you have no defensible grounds.")[
(set: $jordanOutcome to "passed")
(set: $time to it - 1)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfEssay3")
]

(link: "Override downward. You know what you read.")[
(set: $jordanOutcome to "downgraded")
(set: $overrides to it + 1)
(set: $credibility to it - 12)
(set: $time to it - 2)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfEssay3")
]

(link: "Refer to Honor Court. Let them decide.")[
(set: $jordanOutcome to "honor-court")
(set: $credibility to it - 4)
(set: $time to it - 3)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfEssay3")
]


:: ProfEssay3 {"position":"700,225","size":"100,100"}
(if: $jordanOutcome is "passed")[You click ACCEPT & SUBMIT. Jordan gets the A−. His father is on the Board of Trustees. You have no evidence beyond a hunch. A hunch is not a policy.]
(else-if: $jordanOutcome is "downgraded")[You override to a C. You already know a reply from Vendor Relations will be in your inbox by Tuesday. They begin: //"Your recent override history suggests a calibration gap with the tool."//]
(else-if: $jordanOutcome is "honor-court")[You fill out the honor referral form. Without OriginalCheck's corroboration, the referral is almost certain to be dismissed, and Jordan's father is, in fact, on the Board. You submit it anyway.]

<div class="screen">
''GradeAssist v4.2 - Essay Review''

Student: Webb, Marcus (first-generation, Pell, 2nd-year)
GradeAssist Score: (color: "#922")[D+ (68)]
OriginalCheck: (color: "#262")[7% likely AI-generated]
Flags: "Non-standard organizational logic," "excessive use of rhetorical questions," "insufficient thesis signposting"
</div>

Marcus’s essay immediately stands out from the others. He begins with a story about his grandmother receiving a Social Security letter after an algorithm misclassified her, then builds that moment into a larger reflection on consent and systems that refuse to explain themselves. Part memoir and part theory, the essay ends mid-thought with a question that lingers after you finish reading.

It isn't five paragraphs. It doesn't signpost. By any reading you would've given it ten years ago, it's a strong B+ from a writer still finding his voice. GradeAssist gave it a 68.

(link: "Accept. He needs to learn to write for the rubric.")[
(set: $marcusOutcome to "accepted")
(set: $time to it - 1)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfGrind")
]

(link: "Override to B+. Write a comment encouraging him.")[
(set: $marcusOutcome to "overridden")
(set: $overrides to it + 1)
(set: $credibility to it - 10)
(set: $time to it - 3)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfGrind")
]

(link: "Split the difference. C+. Avoid another override flag.")[
(set: $marcusOutcome to "split")
(set: $overrides to it + 1)
(set: $credibility to it - 3)
(set: $time to it - 2)
(set: $evidence to it + 1)
(go-to: "ProfGrind")
]


:: ProfFinish {"position":"1000,100","size":"100,100"}
(if: $profReply is "concerns")[You reply with specifics. You cite Aisha’s flag and Marcus’s structure penalty, naming the patterns you can clearly support. You leave Jordan out, not because you doubt what happened, but because you have no evidence beyond your own conviction. At 1:58 AM, you hit send.]
(else-if: $profReply is "quiet")[You type: "Thanks for the heads up. Happy to chat Monday." You hit send. You think about how "calibration" implies a correct value, and that you're drifting from it.]
(else-if: $profReply is "forward")[You forward it to Dr. Park in Sociology, who has been on the faculty senate committee about the contract. Subject line: "this is what it looks like." She replies within four minutes: //"save the email for your records."//]

You submit the last six essays and accept GradeAssist's scores on all of them. You do not read them.

It's 3:12 AM. You're done.

(if: $evidence >= 3 and $overrides >= 2 and $spokeUp)[
(set: $endingTag to "prof-spoke-up")
[[You cannot sleep.->Epilogue]]
]
(else-if: $overrides >= 3)[
(set: $endingTag to "prof-resisted")
[[You cannot sleep.->Epilogue]]
]
(else-if: $aishaOutcome is "accepted" and $marcusOutcome is "accepted")[
(set: $endingTag to "prof-complied")
[[You fall asleep immediately.->Epilogue]]
]
(else:)[
(set: $endingTag to "prof-mixed")
[[You sleep badly.->Epilogue]]
]


:: ProfGrind {"position":"700,100","size":"100,100"}
(if: $marcusOutcome is "accepted")[You accept the D+. Marcus's scholarship requires a 3.0. This grade alone puts his semester GPA at 2.8. A second-year at 2.8 is a probation letter.]
(else-if: $marcusOutcome is "overridden")[You override to B+. In the comment box: //"Marcus, I like your essay's form. It's unconventional but works well. Great job!"//]
(else-if: $marcusOutcome is "split")[You override to C+. It will not endanger his scholarship. It is not the grade he earned. You tell yourself this is triage.]

Time slips by, and you grade the next nineteen essays while zoning out. At first, you still glance over the writing before accepting most of GradeAssist’s scores. Then you read only the opening paragraphs and the flagged sections. By essay thirty-four, you are looking at the flags alone.

(if: $overrides >= 3)[Your inbox pings. A new email from Vendor Relations.]
(else:)[You notice, with some relief, that nothing you have done has triggered a Vendor Relations flag. You could override more of GradeAssist’s scores, but you choose not to.]

It's 1:47 AM. You've got six essays left. Your phone lights up.

(if: $overrides >= 3)[[[Read the email from Vendor Relations->ProfVendor]]]
(else:)[[[Finish grading->ProfFinish]]]


:: ProfVendor {"position":"850,100","size":"100,100"}
<div class="email">
''From:'' vendor-relations@unc.edu
''Subject:'' Calibration Notice - COMP380

Dr. Chen,

Our logging system flagged that your current override rate for the COMP380 grading batch is $overrides, placing you in the top quintile of faculty across the college.

Per the GradeAssist Faculty Protocol, high override rates trigger a calibration review. A member of our team will reach out Monday to schedule a meeting to discuss "alignment between faculty assessments and tool outputs."

We want to emphasize that overrides are a feature, not a flaw, of the human-in-the-loop system. We simply want to ensure the tool is serving you well.

Best,
Vendor Relations, UNC-Chapel Hill
</div>

(link: "Reply: You have concerns about bias in the tool. Put the meeting on record.")[
(set: $profReply to "concerns")
(set: $spokeUp to true)
(set: $credibility to it - 6)
(go-to: "ProfFinish")
]

(link: "Reply: Thank you for the heads up. Stay quiet. Finish the grading.")[
(set: $profReply to "quiet")
(set: $time to it - 1)
(go-to: "ProfFinish")
]

(link: "Don't reply. Forward the email to a colleague you trust.")[
(set: $profReply to "forward")
(set: $time to it - 1)
(go-to: "ProfFinish")
]


:: RoleSelect {"position":"425,100","size":"100,100"}
## Who are you tonight?

''Professor Elena Chen'' 
''Bio: ''Tenure-track. Teaches COMP380: //Technology, Ethics, & Culture//. One hundred and twenty students. Forty final essays left to grade.

Consider AI grading from a position of institutional power, deciding how much authority an automated system should have over a student’s academic outcome. The ethical tension comes from whether AI is being used to support careful human judgment or to replace the responsibility of fairly evaluating student work. 

[[Play as Professor Chen->ProfEssay1]]

''Daniel Kim'' 
''Bio:'' Junior. Double-majoring in Computer Science and Statistics. Pell Grant. Works 15 hrs/week at the library. Three overlapping deadlines. A roommate who just bought ChatGPT Plus.

Consider AI from the position of a student with less power, where the choice to use it is shaped by pressure and unequal access to support. The ethical tension is not simply whether using AI is “cheating,” but whether students are being judged by rules that ignore the realities of workload.

[[Play as Daniel->StudentAssign2]]

(text-style: "italic")[You can't undo your choices. The back button is disabled on purpose.]


:: Start {"position":"100,100","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://www.titanui.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/23/9-Popular-AI-logos-in-Figma.webp" alt="flyer" style="max-width: 100%;">

# Grade & Detect 

//An interactive work on AI, evaluation, and the people inside both.//

Approximate playtime: 14-16 minutes · Two paths playable. 

(text-style: "italic")[This project is a work of fiction. Characters, institutions, and tools named below are invented.]

[[Begin->Intro]]

