:: StudentLetter {"position":"800,350","size":"100,100"}
(if: $aiUsage >= 2)[Kenzie forwards the letter to your phone. You read it at 2:47 AM in bed.]
(else:)[You find the letter on the class GroupMe. It has been shared sixty-two times. Aisha wrote it herself. It is three paragraphs, then a list of signatures.]

<div class="letter">
''An Open Letter to the Carolina Community''

My name is Aisha Al-Mansoori. I am a junior international student. English is my second language.

Last week I turned in an essay on algorithmic governance. I wrote it myself. I revised it fourteen times. I read it out loud to my roommate to check the rhythm of the sentences, because in Arabic the rhythm of a sentence carries meaning that it does not carry in English, and I did not want to lose that.

The tool flagged my essay as 89% likely AI-generated, and my professor called me in to explain. I showed her my drafts, and she believed me, but the flag was already in the system. So was the grade, and so was the override, recorded as an anomaly against her.

What I want to say is this: the tool did not decide I cheated. It decided my sentences were too clean. Too clean, I think, for a student with my name, though the tool would not put it that way.

I am not the first. International students I know are being told, by friends who mean well, to "sound more casual," to "leave in mistakes on purpose." That is what you tell someone playing a rigged game.

I do not want the tool calibrated. I want someone to ask whether a tool that punishes careful writing has any place in a university.

If you used AI and were cleared, you are the reason I am asking. Please say so, even anonymously.

Aisha
</div>

(if: $aiUsage >= 2)[You close the app and look at the ceiling. You think about the line //"the tool did not decide I cheated. It decided my sentences were too clean."//

You think about Kenzie whose essay the tool didn't touch. You think about the A− sitting in your own gradebook. You think about the guilt you felt at first using AI and how it stopped Saturday afternoon unnoticeably.

The letter includes an anonymous free-text field at the bottom. It asks for feedback from someone directly affected by the system. 

(link: "Sign the open letter. Out yourself anonymously as someone who used AI and wasn't flagged.")[
